| place of burial = 
|}}

{{Nihongo|'''Saionji Shōshi'''|西園寺しょう子, 西園寺鏱子||extra=1271 – 10 June 1342}}, also known as {{Nihongo|'''Eifuku Mon'in'''|永福門院}} (also written Eifuku-mon In), was a celebrated [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[poet]] of the [[Kamakura period]], and a consort of the 92nd emperor, [[Emperor Fushimi|Fushimi]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c8rKCOSmKEMC&dq=%22Saionji+Sh%C5%8Dshi%22&pg=PA273 |title=The Clear Mirror: A Chronicle of the Japanese Court During the Kamakura Period (1185-1333) |date=1998-08-01 |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-6388-2 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JvRSUOMYLeMC&dq=eifuku+mon'in&pg=PA192 |title=The Poetry of Zen |date=2007-02-13 |publisher=Shambhala Publications |isbn=978-0-8348-2508-6 |language=en}}</ref> Her father was the Chancellor Sane-kane.<ref name=":0" />  She was a member of the {{Nihongo|[[Kyōgoku (poetry)|Kyōgoku school of verse]]|[[:ja:京極派|京極派]]|Kyōgoku-ha}}, and her work appears in the ''[[Gyokuyō Wakashū|Gyokuyōshū]]''.<ref>p. 160, Acts of Worship, Yukio Mishima, tr. John Bester, pub. Kodansha, Tokyo, 1990. {{ISBN|0-87011-824-2}}/{{ISBN|4-7700-1507-0}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Louis-Frédéric |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&dq=eifuku+mon'in&pg=PA170 |title=Japan Encyclopedia |date=2002 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-01753-5 |language=en}}</ref>

She became empress in 1288, and though she had no children of her own, she adopted Go-Fushimi.<ref name=":0" />  In 1298, her husband abdicated the throne.<ref name=":1" />  On 23 June 1316 (5th year of [[Shōwa (1312–1317)|Shōwa]]), she took tonsure as a Buddhist nun and was given the [[Dharma name]] '''Shin'nyo Gen''' (真如源).<ref>{{cite web |title=永福門院 |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E6%B0%B8%E7%A6%8F%E9%96%80%E9%99%A2-35985 |website=コトバンク |access-date=2019-10-13 |language=ja}}</ref>

